  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How much does a packaging conveyor system cost?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Conveyor pricing varies widely based on several key factors. There is no single "price" for a conveyor — costs depend on your specific application.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-ink">Key cost factors:</strong></p>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Conveyor type:</strong> gravity roller is the least expensive; spiral and pallet conveyors cost significantly more</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Length and width:</strong> longer runs and wider belts increase cost proportionally</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Materials:</strong> food-grade stainless steel costs more than painted carbon steel</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Controls:</strong> PLC-controlled systems with sensors and VFDs add substantial cost vs. simple on/off</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Environment:</strong> washdown, cleanroom, or hazardous-area ratings increase cost</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Installation:</strong> structural supports, electrical, and integration with existing equipment</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The best approach is to contact manufacturers directly with your specific requirements. See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent font-semibold hover:text-accent-hover">cost factors guide</a> for a detailed breakdown of what drives conveyor pricing.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What type of conveyor is best for packaging lines?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>The right conveyor depends on your product, throughput, and environment:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
              <li><a href="/conveyor-types/flat-belt-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Belt conveyors</a> — lightweight products, irregular shapes, gentle handling</li>
              <li><a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Roller conveyors</a> — cases, cartons, totes (gravity or powered)</li>
              <li><a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> — zone-based accumulation, low maintenance, quiet</li>
              <li><a href="/conveyor-types/tabletop-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Tabletop chain</a> — bottles, cans, small cartons at high speed</li>
              <li><a href="/conveyor-types/spiral-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Spiral conveyors</a> — elevation changes without eating floor space</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Most packaging lines combine multiple types. <a href="/conveyor-types/" class="text-accent font-semibold hover:text-accent-hover">Browse all 30+ types</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is zero-pressure accumulation?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p><strong class="text-ink">Zero-pressure accumulation (ZPA)</strong> means products queue on a conveyor without touching each other or building up backpressure. Each zone has its own photo-eye sensor and independent drive. When a downstream zone is occupied, upstream zones stop their products with controlled gaps between them.</p>
            <p>ZPA prevents product damage, label scuffing, and carton crushing. It's critical for fragile products and high-value items. Most commonly implemented using <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> or <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">pneumatic accumulation conveyors</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How do I calculate conveyor speed for my line?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>The basic conveyor speed formula:</p>
            <p class="font-mono text-ink bg-surface-dim px-4 py-3 border border-border"><strong>Speed (FPM) = (Products/min &times; Product length in ft) + gap allowance</strong></p>
            <p>Common packaging line speeds by application:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Case conveyors:</strong> 50–200 FPM</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Bottle lines:</strong> 20–100 FPM</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">Pallet conveyors:</strong> 20–60 FPM</li>
              <li><strong class="text-ink">High-speed sortation:</strong> 300–600 FPM</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Always add <strong class="text-ink">10–15% speed headroom</strong> above peak production rate so the conveyor never becomes your bottleneck. See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-design-guide/" class="text-accent font-semibold hover:text-accent-hover">design guide</a> for throughput sizing formulas.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the difference between MDR and powered roller?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p><strong class="text-ink">MDR (Motor Driven Roller)</strong> uses small 24VDC brushless motors built inside individual rollers. Each zone (typically 2–5 rollers) operates independently with its own photo-eye and control card. This enables zero-pressure accumulation and zone-by-zone control.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-ink">Powered roller (line-shaft or belt-driven)</strong> uses one external motor driving all rollers through a common belt or chain. All rollers spin together — there's no zone control without additional pneumatic stops or clutches.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-ink">MDR advantages:</strong> 50%+ energy savings (zones only run when needed), quieter (65 dB vs 80+ dB), less maintenance (no belts/chains to replace), better product protection. <strong class="text-ink">Powered roller advantages:</strong> lower upfront cost, simpler for continuous-flow applications with no accumulation requirement.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
